Take aways:

  • There are 27 product categories (classes)
  • Classes are imbalanced, there is one majority class 2583 with 10209 instances, the other 26 classes have between [5073, 764] instances

Questions:

  • What's the product category behind each numerical classes ?
  • Are classes mutually exclusive ?

data = pd.DataFrame()
img_list = glob.glob('images/image_train/*.jpg')
    
for i in range(5):
    try:
        filename = img_list[i]


        img = Image.open(filename)
        img_buffer = io.BytesIO()
        img.save(img_buffer, format="JPEG")
        imgStr = base64.b64encode(img_buffer.getvalue()).decode("utf-8") 

        data.loc[i, 'img'] = '<img src="data:image/jpeg;base64,{0:s}">'.format(imgStr)
        data.loc[i, 'id'] = filename

    except: print('')

data = pd.DataFrame()
for ind, row in enumerate(output[output.index('image_path               \tpredicted_labels         \tconfidence score')+2:]):
    try:
        row = row.split('\t')
        filename = row[0].strip()
#         print(row)
#         print(filename)
        label = row[1].strip()
        conf = row[2].strip()
        img = Image.open(filename)
        img_buffer = io.BytesIO()
        img.save(img_buffer, format="PNG")
        imgStr = base64.b64encode(img_buffer.getvalue()).decode("utf-8") 

        data.loc[ind, 'img'] = '<img src="data:image/png;base64,{0:s}">'.format(imgStr)
        data.loc[ind, 'id'] = filename
        data.loc[ind, 'label'] = label
        data.loc[ind, 'conf'] = conf
        
    except: print('')
